Equity analysis of educational attainment by race for Santa Clara county, CA. Using 2019 ACS 5-yr summary data.

Looking at the data presented for Santa Clara county in CA, it seems that the white alone population has the highest percentage of people who have some college or associates degree but the asian alone population has a higher proportion of individuals who have a bachelors degree or higher. This data used is for populations 25 years or older, so this data could potentially be misrepresenting true statistics of educational attainment, if for example, many individuals under the age of 25 years have received their bachelors degree in recent years. It would be interesting to see data from earlier ages as well to have a more comprehensive understanding of the true comparison between race and educational attainment. The filled plot shows the data in a clearer way than the stacked plot, allowing for comparison among total population and breakdown of different races.

Educational attainment by ethnicity using 2019 ACS 1-yr data.

Looking at the data for Latinx, White not Latinx, and non-white non-Latinx, the Latinx community is overly represented in the less than highschool diploma and "high school graduate categories of educational attainment but very underrepresented in the bachelors degree or higher category. Conversely, thewhite alone" population has a significantly lower proportion of less than high school diploma compared to its total population. This data illustrates that for people over the age of 25, the Latinx population is achieving fewer levels of educational attainment than its white and not-white, not-Latinx counterparts. This could be due to potential lack of opportunity or barriers for Latinx populations that are not the case for white alone populations.
